What is Summary Statistics/Descriptive Statistics?

  • Data gathered for any analysis is useful when it is properly represented for easy comprehension and to help in proper decision making.
  • After we carry out the data analysis, we delineate its summary so as to understand it in a much better way. This is known as summarizing the data.
  • In R we can summarize data as follows:
    • Descriptive/Summary Statistics
    • Tabulation
    • Graphical

Summary Commands in R

  • As an analyst, you need to have an overview of the dataset you are dealing with.
  • There are a few ways of doing this:
    • ls() - used to know the list of named objects that you have.
    • str() - gives the structure of an object (dataset).
    • summary() - gives a statistical summary of your dataset.
Species <- c("Red maple","Aspen","Hackberry","Lodgepole pine","Swamp white oak","Black cherry","Eastern white pine")
 Girth <- c(8.3, 8.6, 8.8, 10.5, 10.7, 10.8, 11.0)  
 Height <- c(70, 65, 63, 72, 81, 83, 66)
 Volume <- c(10.3, 10.3, 10.2, 16.4, 18.8, 19.7, 15.6)
mytrees <- data.frame(Species,Girth,Height,Volume)

Name Commands in R

  • Name command and its variants are used to find or add names to rows and columns of data structures.
    • names() It works on matrix or data frame objects.
    • rownames() It works on matrix or data frame objects and is used to give names to rows.
    • colnames() It works on matrix or data frame objects and is used to give names to columns.
    • dimnames() Gets row and column names for matrix or data frame objects, that is, it is used to see dimensions of the data frame.
names(mytrees)
## [1] "Species" "Girth"   "Height"  "Volume"
rownames(mytrees)
## [1] "1" "2" "3" "4" "5" "6" "7"
colnames(mytrees)
## [1] "Species" "Girth"   "Height"  "Volume"
dimnames(mytrees)
## [[1]]
## [1] "1" "2" "3" "4" "5" "6" "7"
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] "Species" "Girth"   "Height"  "Volume"

Summary Commands

  • Commands that produce a single value as output.
    • max(x, na.rm = FALSE) It shows the maximum value.
    • min(x, na.rm = FALSE) Shows minimum value in a vector.
    • length(x) Gives length of the vector and includes na values.
    • sum(x, na.rm = FALSE) Shows the sum of the vector elements.
    • mean(x, na.rm = FALSE) We obtain an arithmetic mean with this.
    • median( x, na.rm = FALSE) Shows the median value of the vector.
    • sd(x, na.rm = FALSE) Shows the standard deviation.
    • var(x, na.rm = FALSE) Shows the variance.
    • mad(x, na.rm = FALSE) Shows the median absolute deviation.
      • By default, NA values are not removed. Use the na.rm = TRUE instruction to remove NAs for accurate results.
  • Some commands that produce multiple outputs.
    • log(dataset) Shows log value for each element.
    • summary(dataset) We have seen how it shows a summary of dataset like maximum value, minimum value, mean, etc.
    • quantile() Shows the quantiles by defaultthe 0%, 25%, 50%, 75%, and 100% quantiles.
      • If the data contains NA items, you must remove them using the na.rm = TRUE instruction, otherwise, you get an error message.

Simple Cumulative Commands in R

  • These commands need only the name of the object.
  • Cumulative commands produce an accurate result when applied to a vector of numeric data
  • if applied on character data, they give error populated as a list of NA items.
  • If the numeric vector contains NA, the cumulative command will work till first NA and thereafter give all result as NA.
    • Cumsum(x) The cumulative sum of a vector.
    • Cummax(x) The cumulative maximum value.
    • Cumin(x) The cumulative minimum value.
    • Cumprod(x) The cumulative product.
mytrees$Species
## [1] "Red maple"          "Aspen"              "Hackberry"         
## [4] "Lodgepole pine"     "Swamp white oak"    "Black cherry"      
## [7] "Eastern white pine"
mytrees$Girth
## [1]  8.3  8.6  8.8 10.5 10.7 10.8 11.0
cumsum(mytrees$Species)
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion
## [1] NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
cummax(mytrees$Girth)
## [1]  8.3  8.6  8.8 10.5 10.7 10.8 11.0
cummin(mytrees$Girth)
## [1] 8.3 8.3 8.3 8.3 8.3 8.3 8.3
cumprod(mytrees$Girth)
## [1]       8.300      71.380     628.144    6595.512   70571.978  762177.367
## [7] 8383951.034

Descriptive Statistics in R for Data Frames

  • Max(frame) Returns the largest value in the entire data frame (with all numeric variables).
  • Min(frame) Returns the smallest value in the entire data frame.
  • Sum(frame) Returns the sum of the entire data frame.
  • Fivenum(frame) Returns the Tukey summary values for the entire data frame.
  • Length(frame) - Returns the number of columns in the data frame.
  • Summary(frame) Returns the summary for each column.
  • Row Summary Commands Applied to work with row data.
    • rowmeans()
    • rowsums()
  • Column Summary Commands Also, applied to work with row data.
    • colmeans()
    • colsums()
mytrees1 <- data.frame(Girth, Height, Volume)

max(mytrees1)
## [1] 83
min(mytrees1)
## [1] 8.3
sum(mytrees1)
## [1] 670
fivenum(mytrees1$Girth)
## [1]  8.30  8.70 10.50 10.75 11.00
length(mytrees1)
## [1] 3

The apply() Command in R for Summaries

  • Colmeans() and rowsums() commands are quick alternative to a more general command apply().

  • The apply() command enables applying a function to the rows or columns of a matrix or data frame.

  • The general form of the command is: apply(X, MARGIN, FUN, ...)

    • x specifies the matrix or data frame.
    • MARGIN command uses either 1 or 2, where 1 is for rows and 2 is for columns.
    • You replace the FUN part with your command (the function you want to apply).
    • All of the columns or rows should be numeric.
str(mytrees1)
## 'data.frame':    7 obs. of  3 variables:
##  $ Girth : num  8.3 8.6 8.8 10.5 10.7 10.8 11
##  $ Height: num  70 65 63 72 81 83 66
##  $ Volume: num  10.3 10.3 10.2 16.4 18.8 19.7 15.6
max(mytrees1)
## [1] 83

Graphical Summaries

  • Much of the statistical analysis is based on numerical techniques, and these techniques are based on assumptions about the data being used.
  • Graphical data analysis with R, is one way to determine if data satisfy the assumptions.
  • Graphs are useful for non-numerical data.When numerical measures are difficult or impossible to compute, graphs play an important role.
  • Statistical computing is done with the aim to produce high-quality graphics.

Various types of plots

  • Plots with Single Variable You can plot a graph for a single variable.
    • Histogram, hist(y)
    • Pie chart, pie(y)
    • Time series, plot.ts(y)

  • Plots with Two Variables You can plot a graph with two variables.
    • Scatterplot of y against x, plot(x,y).
    • Box-and-whisker plot of y at each factor level. plot(factor,y)
    • Barplot, barplot(y)

  • Plots with Multiple Variables You can plot a graph with multiple variables.

    • The Pairs Function: (pairs(y)) is a matrix of scatterplots of every variable against every other.
    • The Coplot Function: coplot(x,y|z) For conditioning plots where y is plotted against x for different values of z.

  • Special Plots R has low and high-level graphics facilities.

    • Design plots : plot.design() Plot univariate effects of one or more factors, typically for a designed experiment as analyzed by aov().
    • Bubble plots

Ranking Plots in ggplot2

  • We can make fancier plots using ggplot2.
Bar plot
df <- data.frame(
  Category = c("A", "B", "C", "D", "E"),
  Value = c(10, 15, 8, 12, 20)
)
print(df)
##   Category Value
## 1        A    10
## 2        B    15
## 3        C     8
## 4        D    12
## 5        E    20
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(df, aes(x = Category, y = Value, fill = Category)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Bar Plot of Categories",
       x = "Category",
       y = "Value")

Pie Plot
ggplot(df, aes(x = "", y = Value, fill = Category)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 1) +
  coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
  labs(title = "Pie Chart of Categories",
       fill = "Category") +
  theme_void() +
  theme(legend.position = "right")

Showing density and distributions in ggplot2

Histograms
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, fill = Species)) +
  geom_histogram(position = "identity", alpha = 0.5, bins = 20) +
  facet_grid(Species ~ ., scales = "free_y") +
  labs(title = "Paired Histogram of Sepal Length by Species",
       x = "Sepal Length",
       y = "Count")

Curves
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, fill = Species)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5, color = "black") +  
  facet_grid(Species ~ ., scales = "free_y") +
  labs(title = "Paired Histogram of Sepal Length by Species",
       x = "Sepal Length",
       y = "Density/Count")

Box Plots
ggplot(iris, aes(x = Species, y = Sepal.Length, fill = Species)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~Species, scales = "free") +
  labs(title = "Box Plot of Sepal Length for Each Species",
       x = "Species",
       y = "Sepal Length",
       fill = "Species") +
  theme_minimal()

Scatter plot

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Sepal.Width, size = Petal.Length, color = Species)) +

Line Charts
set.seed(123)
data <- data.frame(
  Year = 2000:2020,
  Value = cumsum(rnorm(21))
)

# Line chart
ggplot(data, aes(x = Year, y = Value)) +
  geom_line(color = "blue") +
  geom_point(color = "red", size = 3) +
  labs(title = "Line Chart of Fictional Data",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Value") +
  theme_minimal()

# Area chart
ggplot(data, aes(x = Year, y = Value, fill = "Area")) +
  geom_area(color = "blue", alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_point(color = "red", size = 3) +
  labs(title = "Area Chart of Fictional Data",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Value",
       fill = "") +
  theme_minimal()
